We could skip the extra O(n) traversal here by just replicating the logic in `quantileSorted` ourselves and leaving out the approximation step - we aren't actually using it, given that we define the `extent` based not on the quantile value itself, but on the filtered data.  So it's the same as if we made the approximation use the index 5% of the way into the array (rounded up) and 95% of the way into the array (rounded down), since the result of the filtering is just to truncate the array to that middle section anyway.

So this should be functionally equivalent to what we have now:

```typescript
if (ignoreYOutliers && yPoints.length > 2) {
    yMin = yPoints[Math.ceil((yPoints.length - 1) * 0.05)];
    yMax = yPoints[Math.floor((yPoints.length - 1) * 0.95)];
}
```

Optional since if we change this to use the inter-quartile range or something else a little bit more statistically justified (IMO) we'll probably have to go back to using `filter()`, but just pointing it out in case we stick with this outlier definition.

