Ah, I'm beginning to remember why I went this direction to begin with. As written, the suggested change won't compile, but I'm assuming you meant something more along the lines of:

```
template <ArgType = ElemType>
typename std::enable_if<std::is_same<ArgType, bool>::value, bool>::type
Bool(ArgType b) override {
  this->m_output.push_back(b);
  return true;
}

template <ArgType = ElemType>
typename std::enable_if<std::is_same<ArgType, bool>::value, bool>::type
Bool(ArgType b) {
  return false;
}
```
This won't work either because a template cannot override a virtual function, so the base `Bool` is always called. The alternative is to create a `store_bool` function similar to what I did [here](https://github.com/dmlc/treelite/pull/202/files#diff-38fd03e89a1597a342c7600bd8ccede4R191-R207).

I guess I'd lean slightly toward leaving it as is and adding a comment than adding 2 additional methods, a layer of indirection, and more template metaprogramming, but I'm very happy to be overruled. It makes sense to me because I wrote it, but it's far more important that it makes sense to you and any other developers who will have to work with this later on.

